wiki_catalogs.name: Tool Overview & Core Value
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the proxy-benchmark CLI tool. Explain its purpose as a Go-based utility for measuring and analyzing proxy server performance across HTTP/HTTPS/SOCKS5 protocols. Describe the core value proposition: enabling developers and network engineers to evaluate latency, request response times, and derived processing metrics with statistical rigor. Cover key features including multi-protocol support, warmup phases, ping measurement, request benchmarking, and JSON report generation. Illustrate the high-level workflow from configuration to output, emphasizing ease of integration into testing and monitoring pipelines. Include practical examples of use cases such as comparing commercial proxy providers or validating internal proxy infrastructure. Use terminology consistent with the codebase (e.g., BenchmarkEngine, Metrics, Reporter). Provide a conceptual overview accessible to beginners while detailing technical capabilities relevant to advanced users.

wiki_catalogs.name: Warmup Phase
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the warmup phase of the benchmarking process, focusing on its implementation in the BenchmarkEngine.Run method in benchmark.go. Explain how the warmup phase establishes initial connections to proxies to stabilize their performance before actual measurements begin. Describe the purpose of warming up proxy connections, including mitigating cold-start effects and priming connection pools. Detail how this phase helps achieve more accurate and consistent latency and throughput measurements during subsequent phases. Include code examples showing how runWarmup() is invoked and error handling strategies if warmup fails. Address common issues such as timeouts or authentication errors during warmup and how they affect the overall benchmark execution flow.

wiki_catalogs.name: Metrics Collection
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the metrics collection mechanism implemented in metrics.go. Explain how the Metrics struct serves as a thread-safe data container using sync.Mutex to protect concurrent access during benchmarking phases. Detail the types of metrics collected: total, successful, and failed request counts; individual request durations; ping (TCP connection) times; and derived proxy processing times. Describe how metrics are updated across different stages—warmup, ping, and request benchmarking—and how they are aggregated per proxy. Provide code examples showing how AddRequest and AddPing methods record timing data, and how mutex synchronization prevents race conditions in high-concurrency scenarios. Explain integration points with benchmark.go and client implementations, and discuss performance implications of frequent metric updates under load.

wiki_catalogs.name: Proxy Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the proxy configuration section focused on the Proxies field in the Config struct. Explain that this is a JSON array of strings, each representing a proxy in the format 'protocol://[user:pass@]host:port'. Document supported protocols (http, https, socks5), authentication handling via user:pass credentials, and validation rules enforced during parsing in proxy.go. Clarify how the enabled/disabled status is not directly in the string but controlled by inclusion/exclusion or preprocessing (as implied by filtering logic). Provide real-world examples from config.example.json showing HTTP, HTTPS, and SOCKS5 proxies with and without authentication. Include common mistakes such as incorrect protocol spelling, missing ports, or invalid characters, and explain how these result in parsing errors. Demonstrate how proxy strings are parsed into internal Proxy structs and used by http_client.go and socks5_client.go. Make this accessible to beginners while offering technical depth on format constraints and integration with the benchmarking engine.

wiki_catalogs.name: Installation & Setup
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on installing and setting up the proxy-benchmark tool. Detail both building from source using the provided Makefile and build.sh script, as well as potential binary distribution methods. Document prerequisites such as Go version requirements and external dependencies (golang.org/x/net/proxy, github.com/montanaflynn/stats). Provide step-by-step instructions for cloning the repository, compiling the executable via 'make build', and verifying successful installation. Include guidance on setting up the environment, including PATH configuration. Reference the README.md for quick-start commands and explain how the build process integrates with the project structure. Address common setup issues like missing Go modules or permission errors during compilation. Offer troubleshooting tips and performance considerations for different operating systems.

wiki_catalogs.name: Ping Measurement
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the ping measurement phase, focusing on how TCP connection latency is measured using ping.go and orchestrated by benchmark.go. Explain the role of ping.go in establishing raw TCP connections to proxy servers and measuring the time.Duration required to complete the handshake. Describe how dial timeouts are implemented to prevent hanging operations and ensure reliable measurements. Detail how results are stored in the Metrics structure for later analysis and reporting. Include code examples demonstrating the use of net.DialTimeout and timing logic with time.Now(). Address common network-level issues such as connection resets, firewall blocks, or DNS resolution failures, and explain how these impact ping metrics and downstream calculations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Statistical Analysis
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the statistical analysis functionality in statistics.go. Explain how raw timing data from metrics.go is transformed into meaningful insights using the github.com/montanaflynn/stats library. Cover the calculation of key statistical measures: minimum and maximum values, arithmetic mean, median, standard deviation, and customizable percentile thresholds (e.g., 95th, 99th). Describe the Statistics struct and its derivation from collected request and ping times. Provide concrete examples from the codebase showing how stats.Mean(), stats.Percentile(), and similar functions are invoked. Discuss the importance of these metrics in identifying performance outliers and evaluating proxy reliability. Address potential edge cases such as empty datasets or extreme variance, and explain how the system handles them. Integrate usage context from benchmark.go and reporter.go to show data flow into reporting layers.

wiki_catalogs.name: Benchmark Settings
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the benchmark settings section focused on the BenchmarkConfig struct in config.go. Document each field: TargetURL (endpoint to request during benchmarking), TimeoutSeconds (per-request timeout), RetryAttempts (retries on failure), WarmupRequests (initial warmup phase count), and BenchmarkRequests (main test phase count). Explain the purpose of each setting in the context of accurate performance measurement—e.g., warmup stabilizes connection pools, retries handle transient failures. Use values from config.example.json to illustrate typical configurations. Describe how these settings directly control behavior in benchmark.go phases (warmup, ping, request execution). Address common issues like setting timeouts too low or benchmark counts too high, leading to skewed results or excessive runtime. Provide guidance on tuning these values based on network conditions and testing goals. Link this to the BenchmarkEngine's operation and ensure clarity for both new users and advanced customization.

wiki_catalogs.name: Configuration Guide
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature or sub-component section focused on the configuration system of proxy-benchmark. Thoroughly explain the structure of config.json based on the Config struct in config.go, including fields for proxies array, target URL, timeout settings, retry attempts, warmup requests, benchmark requests, and statistics configuration. Clarify the format for proxy entries (protocol, host, port, username, password, enabled) and provide real examples from config.example.json. Document default values applied when fields are omitted and validation rules enforced by the LoadConfig function. Explain how to enable/disable specific proxies and customize benchmark intensity. Include concrete usage patterns such as configuring multiple proxy types or adjusting percentile calculations. Address common configuration mistakes like malformed JSON or invalid URLs, and provide solutions. Make content accessible to beginners while offering technical depth on how configuration drives the BenchmarkEngine behavior.

wiki_catalogs.name: Request Benchmarking
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the request benchmarking phase, covering how HTTP/HTTPS and SOCKS5 requests are executed through respective proxy types using http_client.go and socks5_client.go, coordinated by benchmark.go. Explain how each client implements protocol-specific logic to route requests via proxies while measuring full round-trip response times. Describe concurrency patterns using goroutines and sync.WaitGroup to parallelize requests across multiple proxies without race conditions. Detail how successful responses are tracked, failed attempts are logged, and metrics are updated atomically. Include code examples showing request execution loops, error recovery strategies, and timeout configurations. Address challenges like TLS handshake failures, proxy authentication requirements, and rate limiting that may affect benchmark accuracy.

wiki_catalogs.name: Report Generation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the report generation system in reporter.go. Explain how the Reporter struct consumes finalized Metrics and Statistics data to produce structured JSON outputs. Differentiate between the two output formats: result.json (detailed per-proxy breakdown including all timing samples) and results_short.json (aggregated summary with success rates, averages, and percentiles). Document the structure of both JSON files, including field meanings and data types. Provide examples of how reports are written to disk and how users can integrate them into monitoring pipelines or dashboards. Include practical guidance on interpreting success rate calculations (successful/total requests) and detecting underperforming proxies via latency spikes. Reference real-world outputs from test runs and link to sample files in the repository. Address error handling during file writing and extensibility options for future output formats.

wiki_catalogs.name: Statistics Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the statistics configuration section focused on the StatisticsConfig struct in config.go. Explain fields Percentiles and ExcludeOutliers, detailing how Percentiles (e.g., [50, 75, 90, 95, 99]) trigger calculation of corresponding response time percentiles using github.com/montanaflynn/stats. Clarify that ExcludeOutliers enables statistical filtering to remove extreme values that could skew results. Connect this to statistics.go where calculations like Mean, Median, StdDev, and Percentile are implemented. Show examples from config.example.json demonstrating custom percentile sets. Explain how these settings influence the final output in result.json and results_short.json. Address potential misconfigurations such as empty percentile arrays or misunderstanding outlier exclusion impact. Provide best practices for selecting meaningful percentiles based on use case (e.g., SLO monitoring vs. performance profiling). Ensure understanding of how statistical rigor improves result reliability.

wiki_catalogs.name: Command Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the command-line interface of proxy-benchmark. Document the primary execution method via 'go run main.go' or the compiled binary, explaining how flags are parsed using Go's flag package. List all available command-line options such as -config, -target, -timeout, and their overrides of configuration file values. Specify the syntax, data types, and default behaviors for each flag. Provide practical examples demonstrating common invocation patterns, including overriding the target URL or increasing request counts dynamically. Explain the relationship between CLI flags and the Config struct initialization in main.go. Include guidance on combining flags with configuration files and describe error handling for invalid inputs. Address debugging scenarios where command-line overrides help isolate issues.

wiki_catalogs.name: Derived Metrics Calculation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the derived metrics calculation phase, focusing on how proxy processing time is computed as the difference between request time and ping time in benchmark.go. Explain the significance of this derived metric in isolating the proxy server's internal processing overhead from network latency. Describe how calculateDerivedMetrics() iterates over collected data in the Metrics structure to compute and store these values. Detail how this enables more granular performance comparisons between proxies with similar total response times but different processing efficiencies. Include code examples illustrating the subtraction logic and storage mechanism. Address edge cases such as inconsistent timings, negative values due to clock precision, and how statistical smoothing is applied in later stages.

wiki_catalogs.name: Benchmarking Process
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature or sub-component section focused on the end-to-end benchmarking workflow orchestrated by the BenchmarkEngine in benchmark.go. Break down the sequential phases: warmup, ping measurement, and request benchmarking. Explain the purpose of warmup in stabilizing proxy connections before measurement. Detail how ping.go measures TCP connection latency using time.Duration and dial timeouts. Describe how http_client.go and socks5_client.go implement protocol-specific request execution through respective proxy types. Cover concurrency patterns using goroutines for parallel proxy evaluation and synchronization via WaitGroup. Explain derived metric calculation (proxy processing time = request time - ping time) and its significance. Include code examples showing phase transitions and error handling strategies. Address common issues like connection resets or authentication failures during benchmarking and how they impact results.

wiki_catalogs.name: Metrics & Results
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature or sub-component section focused on metrics collection, statistical analysis, and reporting mechanisms. Explain how the Metrics struct in metrics.go serves as a thread-safe container for timing data using sync.Mutex protection during concurrent writes. Detail the types of collected data: total/successful/failed requests, request durations, ping times, and derived processing times. Describe how statistics.go leverages the montanaflynn/stats library to compute min, max, mean, median, standard deviation, and custom percentiles. Explain the role of reporter.go in generating both detailed (result.json) and summary (results_short.json) outputs, mapping Metrics and Statistics to JSON structures. Provide examples of interpreting result files, including success rate calculation and outlier detection. Address data accuracy concerns and performance implications of extensive metric collection.

wiki_catalogs.name: Technical Architecture
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the core components of proxy-benchmark. Describe the high-level design as a modular monolith with clear separation of concerns between configuration, benchmarking, metrics, and reporting layers. Highlight architectural patterns used: Factory Pattern (NewBenchmarkEngine, NewReporter), Strategy Pattern (conditional client selection by protocol), Observer Pattern (metrics observation during benchmark phases), and Dependency Injection (passing Config throughout components). Illustrate component interactions through data flow: main.go → BenchmarkEngine → Proxy list → Client implementations → Metrics → Reporter. Explain the concurrency model using goroutines per proxy and mutex-protected shared state. Discuss technical decisions like choosing JSON for configuration/reporting and Go's native concurrency primitives over channels for simplicity. Include a conceptual diagram showing system boundaries and integration points.

wiki_catalogs.name: Development Guide
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on contributing to and extending the proxy-benchmark codebase. Document the development workflow using the Makefile targets: 'make build', 'make test', and 'make clean'. Explain how to run unit tests, particularly metrics_test.go, and how to write new tests for added functionality. Provide guidelines for code organization, naming conventions, and logging practices consistent with existing code. Detail steps for setting up a local development environment with proper Go module configuration. Include contribution procedures such as branching strategy, pull request expectations, and code review criteria. Address extension possibilities like adding new proxy protocols or output formats, highlighting extensibility points in the current architecture. Mention dependency management via go.mod and version compatibility considerations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Troubleshooting
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature or sub-component section focused on diagnosing and resolving common issues encountered when using proxy-benchmark. Catalog frequent problems such as connection timeouts, authentication failures, malformed proxy strings, and empty result files. Map each issue to potential root causes in the codebase—for example, timeout errors relating to dialer configurations in ping.go or http_client.go. Provide diagnostic steps like enabling verbose logging (if implemented), checking network connectivity, and validating proxy credentials. Offer solutions such as adjusting timeout values, correcting proxy formatting in config.json, or ensuring target URL accessibility. Include performance-related troubleshooting like handling high-latency proxies that skew results. Reference error handling patterns in main.go and benchmark.go to guide users in interpreting failure modes.

wiki_catalogs.name: Examples & Use Cases
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature or sub-component section focused on practical applications of proxy-benchmark. Present a basic usage example starting from copying config.example.json to config.json and running the default benchmark. Showcase advanced configurations using test-config.json as a reference, demonstrating scenarios like mixed protocol environments, large proxy pools, or customized statistical analysis. Illustrate real-world use cases such as evaluating residential vs. datacenter proxies, monitoring service degradation over time, or stress-testing failover mechanisms. Provide complete, runnable configuration snippets with explanations of key parameters. Highlight how different settings affect outcomes—for instance, increasing benchmark_requests improves statistical reliability. wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Proxy Benchmark Tool Analysis

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
The proxy-benchmark project is a Go-based tool designed to evaluate and compare the performance of multiple proxy servers under controlled conditions. It measures various metrics including connection latency, request response times, and derived processing times.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Benchmark proxy server performance across different protocols (HTTP/HTTPS/SOCKS5)
- Measure both direct TCP connection times (ping) and actual HTTP request performance
- Calculate derived metrics that isolate proxy processing overhead
- Generate comprehensive reports with statistical analysis of performance data
- Provide a simple interface for comparing multiple proxies simultaneously

### Target Audience
- Network administrators evaluating proxy server performance
- Developers testing proxy configurations
- Security professionals assessing network infrastructure
- Researchers studying network performance characteristics

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The application follows a modular architecture with clear separation of concerns:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[main.go] --> B[Configuration]
    A --> C[Benchmark Engine]
    A --> D[Reporter]
    B --> E[config.go]
    C --> F[proxy.go]
    C --> G[http_client.go]
    C --> H[socks5_client.go]
    C --> I[ping.go]
    C --> J[metrics.go]
    D --> K[reporter.go]
    J --> L[statistics.go]
```

### Design Patterns
- **Factory Pattern**: Used in `NewBenchmarkEngine`, `NewReporter`, and client constructors
- **Strategy Pattern**: Different proxy protocols are handled through conditional logic in benchmark execution
- **Observer Pattern**: Metrics collection throughout the benchmarking process
- **Dependency Injection**: Configuration is passed through the application layers

### System Relationships
```mermaid
graph TD
    main[Main Application] --> config[Configuration Loader]
    main --> engine[Benchmark Engine]
    main --> reporter[Result Reporter]
    
    engine --> proxy[Proxy Manager]
    engine --> http[HTTP Client]
    engine --> socks[SOCKS5 Client]
    engine --> ping[Ping Client]
    engine --> metrics[Metrics Collector]
    
    metrics --> stats[Statistics Calculator]
    
    reporter --> output[JSON Report Generator]
    
    config -.->|Provides configuration| engine
    engine -.->|Provides results| reporter
```

### Data Flow
```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Command Line] --> B[Configuration File]
    B --> C[Config Parser]
    C --> D[Benchmark Engine]
    D --> E[Proxy List]
    E --> F[Warmup Phase]
    E --> G[Ping Measurement]
    E --> H[Request Benchmarking]
    F --> I[Metrics Collection]
    G --> I
    H --> I
    I --> J[Statistics Calculation]
    J --> K[Report Generation]
    K --> L[JSON Output Files]
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- [main.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/main.go)

### Core Modules
- [benchmark.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/benchmark.go): Orchestrates the entire benchmarking process
- [config.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/config.go): Handles configuration loading and parsing
- [metrics.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/metrics.go): Manages performance metric collection and storage
- [reporter.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/reporter.go): Generates final reports in JSON format

### Configuration Approach
- [config.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/config.go): Implements JSON-based configuration with default values
- [config.example.json](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/config.example.json): Provides example configuration structure

### External Dependencies
- [go.mod](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/go.mod): Not visible in current context but implied by import statements
- golang.org/x/net/proxy: For SOCKS5 proxy support in [socks5_client.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/socks5_client.go)
- github.com/montanaflynn/stats: For statistical calculations in [statistics.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/statistics.go)

### Integration Points
- [http_client.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/http_client.go): Integrates with Go's standard HTTP library for HTTP/HTTPS proxies
- [socks5_client.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/socks5_client.go): Integrates with golang.org/x/net/proxy for SOCKS5 support
- [ping.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/ping.go): Uses Go's net package for direct TCP connection measurement

### Component Relationships
```mermaid
graph LR
    main[main.go] --> config[config.go]
    main --> benchmark[benchmark.go]
    main --> reporter[reporter.go]
    
    config --> proxy[proxy.go]
    
    benchmark --> proxy
    benchmark --> http[http_client.go]
    benchmark --> socks[socks5_client.go]
    benchmark --> ping[ping.go]
    benchmark --> metrics[metrics.go]
    
    metrics --> stats[statistics.go]
    
    benchmark --> reporter
    
    http -.->|Uses| net[Go net/http]
    socks -.->|Uses| xnet[golang.org/x/net/proxy]
    ping -.->|Uses| net[Go net]
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
The tool provides comprehensive proxy performance testing with three distinct phases:
1. Warmup phase to establish connections
2. Ping measurement for direct TCP connection latency
3. Request benchmarking for actual HTTP performance

### Implementation Highlights
- [main.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/main.go#L0-L81): Main application flow with command-line argument parsing and orchestration
- [benchmark.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/benchmark.go#L39-L75): Comprehensive benchmark execution with multiple phases
- [config.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/config.go#L32-L47): Robust configuration loading with error handling
- [proxy.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/proxy.go#L18-L32): Flexible proxy string parsing supporting multiple protocols
- [metrics.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/metrics.go#L64-L83): Thread-safe metrics collection with mutex protection

### Feature Architecture
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Initialization
    Initialization --> Configuration: Load config.json
    Configuration --> ProxyValidation: Parse and validate proxies
    ProxyValidation --> WarmupPhase: Execute warmup requests
    WarmupPhase --> PingMeasurement: Measure TCP connection times
    PingMeasurement --> RequestBenchmarking: Execute target URL requests
    RequestBenchmarking --> StatisticsCalculation: Calculate min/max/mean/percentiles
    StatisticsCalculation --> ReportGeneration: Create detailed and summary reports
    ReportGeneration --> Complete: Save result.json and results_short.json
    Complete --> [*]
```

Sources:

- [config.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/config.go)
- [benchmark.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/benchmark.go)
- [metrics.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/metrics.go)
- [reporter.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/reporter.go)
- [proxy.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/proxy.go)
- [http_client.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/http_client.go)
- [socks5_client.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/socks5_client.go)
- [ping.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/ping.go)
- [statistics.go](/Users/suenot/proxy-benchmark/statistics.go)
</blog>
